<DOC><DOCNO> AP890420-0148 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 2021EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-ForeignSales     04-20 0145</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Foreign Sales,140</SECOND><HEAD>Greek Sale Approved</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. government has agreed to sell Greece60 tanks worth $26 million and 16 Harpoon missiles, missilecontainers and contracting services worth $19 million, the Pentagonsaid Thursday.   In addition, the government plans to sell 250 Maverick missiles,their support equipment, publications and training and technicalassistance to Spain at a cost of $48 million.   The foreign sales are subject to congressional approval.   The M48A5 tanks are no longer in production and will come fromexcess stock. The department, in a statement, said Greece needs thetanks to upgrade its tank fleet and increase its military defensecapability.   The prime contractor of the Harpoon missiles will beMcDonnell-Douglas Astronautics Co., of St. Louis, Mo., thedepartment said.   A prime contractor on the missile sale to Spain will be madeafter the competitive bidding process.</TEXT></DOC>